    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "> The stated problem is that there is a _system-wide_ limit on the number of PTYs. I'm not convinced that setting a per-test-process limit on the PTYs is a good idea.\r\n> \r\n> First of all, there will be more than just our Go tests running on most systems, and so other things outside our control could consume PTYs and cause tests to fail in spite of this system.\r\n> \r\n> Secondly, it likely makes for inefficient use of PTYs. Packages that use a lot of PTYs will saturate at 1/8th the total available even if nothing else is using the remaining 7/8ths of the available resources.\r\n> \r\n> Just conceptually, the Kernel is managing the PTY resources from a system-wide pool. We shouldn't also need to separately manage the same resources. If, as this PR is designed, we are willing to wait up to 30s to obtain a PTY if one is not immediately available, why not just retry with a short backoff (e.g. 1s)?\r\n\r\n@spikecurtis This approach was originally introduced by you and @mafredri :\r\nhttps://github.com/coder/internal/issues/558#issuecomment-2857260671\r\nBut I agree with both points.\r\n\r\n`why not just retry with a short backoff (e.g. 1s)`- yeah, that's probably a better idea.\r\n\r\n`UPD`: I see that there are a lot of fair critique, so going to close this PR and reopen new one which will rely on:\r\n- retries proposed by Spike\r\n- increasing limits if it's possible\r\n?",
